{
  "text": "Waist circumference was significantly associated with systolic and diastolic blood pressure, independently of age and puberty stage. This is in accordance with data reported Waist circumference and disease risk C Maffeis et al for obese women on whom computed tomography was used to measure intra-abdominal and subcutaneous fat to investigate the relationship between blood pressure and fat distribution [CITATION_1] . In particular, the Authors found a correlation between the ratio of intra-abdominal visceral fat to subcutaneous fat area ratio and blood pressure, that was independent of age and BMI by multiple regression analysis.",
